Achint ERP — database migrations (Alembic)
==========================================

This folder holds version-controlled schema migrations for the ERP database.

How it relates to ensure_schema_columns()
-----------------------------------------
`main.ensure_schema_columns()` is kept as a runtime safety net so the app boots
even when the database has not yet been Alembic-stamped. New schema work
should be authored as Alembic revisions; `ensure_schema_columns()` is now
considered deprecated for new columns / tables.

First-time setup
----------------
1. Brand-new database:
       python -m main      # boots once, runs Base.metadata.create_all
       alembic stamp head

2. Existing production database (already running):
       alembic stamp head      # one-time anchor; do NOT run upgrade first

After this, every schema change ships as a new revision.

Adding a new schema change
--------------------------
1. Edit `models.py` (add column, table, index, etc.).
2. Generate a revision:
       alembic revision --autogenerate -m "<short description>"
3. Review the generated file in `alembic/versions/` carefully:
   - Confirm only the intended changes are present.
   - For SQLite ALTERs (column drops, type changes, renames), ensure the
     autogenerated `op.batch_alter_table(...)` block is correct.
4. Commit the migration file.
5. Apply:
       alembic upgrade head

Useful commands
---------------
  alembic current        # which revision is the DB at
  alembic history        # full revision graph
  alembic check          # are models and DB in sync? (no diff = clean)
  alembic upgrade head   # apply all pending migrations
  alembic downgrade -1   # revert the most recent migration

Database URL resolution
-----------------------
`alembic/env.py` resolves the URL in this order:
  1. `APP_DATABASE_URL` environment variable (preferred — same var the app uses)
  2. `sqlalchemy.url` in `alembic.ini`
  3. Default fallback `sqlite:///./erp_database.sqlite`

This means ANY environment that already runs the app correctly will run
Alembic against the same database without extra configuration.
